Skyrim

Nords

Illustration of a Nord male

Summary:

  • Homeland of the Nords.

  • Makes up the northern part of Tamriel.

  • Basically Northern Europe.

  • Borders High Rock to the west, Hammerfell to the southwest, Morrowind to the East, and Cyrodiil to the south.

Real-world counterpart/inspiration:

Scandanavia/Eastern Europe (VIKINGS!!!)

  • It is a mostly cold and mountainous province to the north, but the southern regions near Cyrodiil have a more temperate climate in comparison.

  • Skyrim holds four of the five highest mountains in Tamriel, with Red Mountain being the only one outside Skyrim.

  • Many past battles have given it a ravaged appearance, with centuries-old ruins dotting the landscape.

  • Among these ruins are:

    • Nordic Barrows and ancestral burial mounds
    • Dragon burial mounds
    • Dwarven ruins
    • Falmer ruins

  • To the north, the Sea of Ghosts runs along the province's long northern coastline.

  • The border between Skyrim and Morrowind is marked by the Velothi Mountains to the east.

  • The border between Skyrim, High Rock, Hammerfell, and the newest incarnation of Orsinium is marked by the Druadach Mountains to the west and southwest.

  • The border between Skyrim and Cyrodiil is marked by the Jerall Mountains to the south.
  • Skyrim consists of nine holds, each governed by a Jarl:
  • Eastmarch
    • Eastern hold of Skyrim, containing one of the only land passages to and from Morrowind.
    • Contains the ancient city of Windhelm, the oldest continuously inhabited human settlement in Tamriel.
    • Most of the province is rural due to the expansive hot springs which dominate the hold, preventing any meaningful urbanization.

      • Eastmarch

  • The Pale
    • North-central hold of Skyrim.
    • Much of the region is barren, inhospitable and lacks sushine, consisting of boreal pine forests, snowy tundras and wastelands.
    • The region acquired its name from both the pale white tundra and the pigmentation of the local Nords.
    • Contains the port city of Dawnstar, where most, if not all, of the hold's population is centralized.

      • The Pale

  • Winterhold
    • Northeast hold of Skyrim.
    • With inhospitable terrain and snow-blown landscape, there is little to no agriculture or livestock.
    • Due to its geography and climate, this region is relatively isolated from the rest of Tamriel, and is not regarded with much importance by most people.
    • Arguably the only thing of interest here is the College of Winterhold.

      • Winterhold

  • Haafingar
    • Northwestern hold in Skyrim.
    • Relatively small and mountainout.
    • It is separated from the rest of Skyrim by the great Karth River and the massive Karth delta.
    • While most of the hold is made up of mountains, at the foot of these mountains are pine forests and a more temperate climate.
    • Contains the city of Solitude and the settlement of Dragon Bridge.

      • Haafingar

  • Hjaalmarch
    • Northern hold of Skyrim, wedged in between the holds of The Pale and Haafingar.
    • Roughly half the hold is made up of swamps and marshy lowlands, occasionaly cloaked under a dense and mysterious fog.
    • Contains the city of Morthal.
    • The region is veined with waterways that empty into the Sea of Ghosts.
    • Hjaalmarch has the lowest taxes of the nine holds, but it is also the poorest hold.

      • Hjaalmarch

  • The Reach
    • Southwestern hold of Skyrim.
    • The territory once extended into High Rock, but that portion was split off to create the Western Reach region of High Rock.
    • The hold is almost entirely within the vast Druadach Mountain range, and a bit of the Jerall Mountains towards the south.
    • It is made up of hundreds of jagged peaks, steep cliffs and canyons.
    • The Karth River cuts through these mountains, forming several valley canyons.
    • Contains the city of Markarth.
    • Control over The Reach is disputed between the Nords and the native Reachmen, and there has always been deep conflict between the two peoples.

      • The Reach (Skyrim)

  • Whiterun Hold
    • Central hold of Skyrim.
    • The hold is relatively flat, while surrounded by mountains on all sides, and consists of vast fertile lands and tundra plains.
    • It is ideal hunting ground for the local hunters and pasture for the farmers.
    • Because of Whiterun's position at the center of Skyrim, it prospers as being a major trading hub.
    • With numerous and well-maintained roads, Whiterun has excellent access to any of the other holds in Skyrim.
    • Contains the city of Whiterun and the settlements of Rorikstead and Riverwood.
    • Surrounding the capital city are fertile plains dotted with farms that supply the food for much of Skyrim.

      • Whiterun

  • Falkreath Hold
    • Southern hold of Skyrim.
    • Consists of lush pine forests and a significantly large body of freshwater, known as Lake Illinalta, that takes up the hold's center.
    • The hold is the main land route between Skyrim and Cyrodiil, making it an important region for the Imperials to maintain connections with Skyrim.
    • Contains the city of Falkreath and the settlement of Helgen.
    • Thanks to its temperate climate and rich ecosystem, the people of Falkreath Hold can prosper as farmers and loggers.
    • Throughout history, Falkreath has shifted hands between Skyrim and Cyrodiil.

      • Falkreath Hold

  • The Rift
    • Southeastern hold of Skyrim, containing one of the only land passages to and from Morrowind.
    • Due to the surrounding mountains blocking the cold winds, The Rift has a temperate climate and an autumn forest made up of deciduous birch trees, making it distinct in appearance from the rest of Skyrim.
    • Running through middle of the hold are the two twin lakes, Geir and Honrich, and the Treva River that connects them.
    • Contains the city of Riften, situated at the edge of Lake Honrich, and the settlements of Shor's Stone and Ivarstead.
    • The Rift's rich environment allows it to boast a wide variety of fauna and flora.
    • The people of The Rift are able to prosper in farming and fishing, but are also able to spring up industries such as mead-brewing, due to the climate being perfect for raising bees.

      • The Rift
